     8→
     9→# 🎛  PaletteFlow Studio Plugin Lifecycle Hooks
    10→
    11→Plugins in PaletteFlow Studio are *capability-oriented*: they only run when the
    12→host decides they are relevant to the current workspace & user settings.  
    13→The Plugin Runtime therefore exposes a small—but powerful—set of lifecycle
    14→hooks that let you:
    15→
    16→* Allocate resources when the plugin is activated and free them later
    17→* React to workspace, node or theme changes
    18→* Intercept save/export pipelines
    19→* Cleanly integrate with the command palette & settings system
    20→
    21→```mermaid
    22→stateDiagram-v2
    23→    state "Host Process\n(Electron Main)" as H
    24→    state "Renderer Window\n(Vite + React)" as R
    25→    state "Plugin Runtime\n(ESM sandbox)" as P
    26→
    27→    H   --> R : boot
    28→    R   --> P : dynamic import()
    29→    P   --> R : register hooks
    30→    R   --> P : hook callbacks
    31→```
    32→
    33→<br>
    34→
    35→## 1. Quick reference
    36→
    37→| Hook                              | Signature                                                                                               | When it fires                                                        |
    38→| --------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------- |
    39→| `onActivate`                      | `(ctx: ActivationContext) ⇒ Disposable\|void`                                                           | **Once** when the plugin is loaded into a renderer process           |
    40→| `onDeactivate`                    | `(ctx: DeactivationContext) ⇒ void`                                                                     | **Once** before the sandbox is torn down                             |
    41→| `onWorkspaceLoad`                 | `(workspace: WorkspaceHandle, opts: WorkspaceLoadOptions) ⇒ Promise\<void\>`                            | Whenever a workspace becomes the current editing target              |
    42→| `onBeforeSave`                    | `(workspace: WorkspaceHandle) ⇒ Promise\<void\>`                                                        | Right before the host serialises a workspace to disk                 |
    43→| `onNodeCreate`                    | `(node: NodeHandle, api: NodeLifecycleAPI) ⇒ void`                                                      | Each time the user creates a new node                                |
    44→| `onNodeRender`                    | `(node: NodeHandle, canvas: CanvasRenderingContext2D) ⇒ void|Promise\<void\>`                           | Whenever the node should be drawn on the viewport                    |
    45→| `onSettingsChange`                | `(delta: DeepPartial\<PluginSettings>) ⇒ void`                                                          | Any time the plugin’s user-configurable settings are patched         |
    46→| `onUnhandledError`                | `(err: unknown, ctx: ErrorContext) ⇒ void`                                                              | Whenever an uncaught error bubbles up inside the plugin runtime      |
    47→
    48→All hooks are **optional**.  
    49→Export only what you need:
    50→
    51→```ts
    52→// my-awesome-plugin/index.ts
    53→import type {
    54→  ActivationContext,
    55→  NodeLifecycleAPI,
    56→  PluginSettings,
    57→  WorkspaceHandle
    58→} from '@paletteflow/studio/plugin-api';
    59→
    60→export const onActivate = (ctx: ActivationContext) => {
    61→  // …
    62→};
    63→
    64→export const onNodeCreate = (node: NodeHandle, api: NodeLifecycleAPI) => {
    65→  // …
    66→};
    67→```
    68→
    69→<br>
    70→
    71→## 2. Hook Definitions
    72→
    73→The following TypeScript interfaces live in `@paletteflow/studio/plugin-api`
    74→(they are bundled with the desktop app and version-pinned).
    75→
    76→```ts
    77→/* eslint-disable @typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any */
    78→export interface Disposable {
    79→  /** Free resources allocated during onActivate. */
    80→  dispose(): void | Promise<void>;
    81→}
    82→
    83→export interface ActivationContext {
    84→  readonly version: string;                     // PaletteFlow version e.g. "1.8.0"
    85→  readonly pluginId: string;                    // e.g. "com.acme.colour-swatches"
    86→  readonly logger: Logger;                      // Namespaced logger
    87→  readonly commandRegistry: CommandRegistry;    // Register palette actions
    88→  readonly settings: Readonly<PluginSettings>;  // Initial settings
    89→  readonly env: 'production' | 'development';   // Sandbox environment
    90→}
    91→
    92→export interface DeactivationContext {
    93→  readonly reason: 'app-quit' | 'plugin-update' | 'hot-reload';
    94→}
    95→
    96→export interface WorkspaceLoadOptions {
    97→  firstLoad: boolean; // true = the workspace has just been opened
    98→  origin: 'file-open' | 'hot-reload' | 'undo-redo';
    99→}
   100→
   101→export interface ErrorContext {
   102→  hook: keyof PluginModule; // Which hook threw
   103→  fatal: boolean;           // Will PaletteFlow crash if not handled?
   104→}
   105→```
   106→
   107→<br>
   108→
   109→## 3. Writing robust lifecycle code
   110→
   111→Below is a *complete* plugin showcasing best practices—cancellable disposables,
   112→solid error handling, and CI-friendly TypeScript.
   113→
   114→```ts
   115→/**
   116→ * Colour Swatch Nodes — A demonstration plugin that adds a “ColourSwatch”
   117→ * node type which renders an interactive palette of brand colours.  Users
   118→ * can double-click any swatch to copy its hex code to clipboard.
   119→ *
   120→ * @module com.acme.colour-swatches
   121→ */
   122→import {
   123→  ActivationContext,
   124→  DeactivationContext,
   125→  NodeLifecycleAPI,
   126→  PluginModule,
   127→  WorkspaceHandle
   128→} from '@paletteflow/studio/plugin-api';
   129→
   130→import { z } from 'zod'; // Runtime schema validation
   131→
   132→// 1) -----------------  Settings schema  ------------------------------------
   133→const SettingsSchema = z.object({
   134→  defaultPalette: z.array(z.string().regex(/^#([0-9a-f]{3}){1,2}$/i))
   135→});
   136→
   137→export type PluginSettings = z.infer<typeof SettingsSchema>;
   138→
   139→let disposables: (() => unknown)[] = [];
   140→let settings: PluginSettings;
   141→
   142→export const onActivate: PluginModule['onActivate'] = (ctx: ActivationContext) => {
   143→  // ── Validate settings coming from host ────────────────────────────
   144→  const result = SettingsSchema.safeParse(ctx.settings);
   145→  if (!result.success) {
   146→    ctx.logger.error('Invalid settings payload', result.error.flatten());
   147→    // Fallback to built-in palette
   148→    settings = { defaultPalette: ['#ffb703', '#fb8500', '#023047'] };
   149→  } else {
   150→    settings = result.data;
   151→  }
   152→
   153→  // ── Register a command-palette action ─────────────────────────────
   154→  const disposeCommand = ctx.commandRegistry.register({
   155→    id: `${ctx.pluginId}.insertDefaultSwatch`,
   156→    title: 'Insert Default Colour Swatch',
   157→    run: async () => {
   158→      try {
   159→        const workspace = await ctx.getActiveWorkspace();
   160→        const node = await workspace.nodes.create({
   161→          kind: 'ColourSwatch',
   162→          meta: { palette: settings.defaultPalette }
   163→        });
   164→        ctx.logger.info(`Inserted ColourSwatch node ${node.id}`);
   165→      } catch (err) {
   166→        ctx.logger.error('Failed to insert swatch node', err);
   167→      }
   168→    }
   169→  });
   170→
   171→  disposables.push(disposeCommand);
   172→
   173→  // Return a Disposable so the host can call it on plugin reload
   174→  return {
   175→    dispose: async () => {
   176→      for (const dispose of disposables.splice(0)) {
   177→        await dispose();
   178→      }
   179→    }
   180→  };
   181→};
   182→
   183→export const onDeactivate = (_ctx: DeactivationContext) => {
   184→  // Ensure we free our resources even if the host forgets
   185→  for (const dispose of disposables.splice(0)) {
   186→    // Ignore individual failures but log them
   187→    try {
   188→      dispose();
   189→    } catch (err) {
   190→      /* eslint-disable-next-line no-console */
   191→      console.warn('dispose() failed during onDeactivate', err);
   192→    }
   193→  }
   194→};
   195→
   196→export const onWorkspaceLoad: PluginModule['onWorkspaceLoad'] = async (
   197→  workspace: WorkspaceHandle
   198→) => {
   199→  // Migrate legacy node metadata if needed
   200→  const nodes = await workspace.nodes.findByKind('ColourSwatch', { limit: 1000 });
   201→  for (const node of nodes) {
   202→    if (!Array.isArray(node.meta.palette)) {
   203→      await node.patch({ meta: { palette: settings.defaultPalette } });
   204→    }
   205→  }
   206→};
   207→
   208→/**
   209→ * Register per-node behaviour — called every time a ColourSwatch node is created.
   210→ * We attach an onClick listener that copies colour codes to clipboard.
   211→ */
   212→export const onNodeCreate: PluginModule['onNodeCreate'] = (
   213→  node,
   214→  api: NodeLifecycleAPI
   215→) => {
   216→  if (node.kind !== 'ColourSwatch') return; // Ignore other node types
   217→
   218→  api.events.on('click', async (evt) => {
   219→    const targetHex = (evt.target as HTMLElement)?.dataset['hex'];
   220→    if (!targetHex) return;
   221→
   222→    try {
   223→      await navigator.clipboard.writeText(targetHex);
   224→      api.toast.success(`${targetHex} copied to clipboard`);
   225→    } catch (err) {
   226→      api.toast.error('Unable to access clipboard');
   227→      api.logger.error('clipboard.writeText failed', err);
   228→    }
   229→  });
   230→};
   231→
   232→/**
   233→ * Custom renderer hook — PaletteFlow calls this whenever the node becomes
   234→ * visible.  We render a row of coloured squares on the canvas.
   235→ */
   236→export const onNodeRender: PluginModule['onNodeRender'] = (node, ctx) => {
   237→  if (node.kind !== 'ColourSwatch') return;
   238→
   239→  const palette: string[] = node.meta.palette ?? settings.defaultPalette;
   240→  const { width, height } = node.dimensions;
   241→
   242→  const swatchWidth = width / palette.length;
   243→
   244→  palette.forEach((hex, idx) => {
   245→    ctx.fillStyle = hex;
   246→    ctx.fillRect(idx * swatchWidth, 0, swatchWidth, height);
   247→  });
   248→};
   249→
   250→export const onUnhandledError: PluginModule['onUnhandledError'] = (
   251→  err,
   252→  { hook }
   253→) => {
   254→  // Funnel all uncaught errors to an external error tracker
   255→  import('@paletteflow/studio/crash-reporter').then(({ report }) => {
   256→    report({
   257→      plugin: 'com.acme.colour-swatches',
   258→      hook,
   259→      error: err instanceof Error ? err : new Error(String(err))
   260→    });
   261→  });
   262→};
   263→```
   264→
   265→<br>
   266→
   267→## 4. Returning Disposables
   268→
   269→`onActivate` can synchronously return `void` **or** a `Disposable` (sync or
   270→async).  The host invokes `dispose()` when:
   271→
   272→* The plugin is reloaded (during development hot-reload)
   273→* The plugin is disabled from Settings
   274→* The application quits
   275→
   276→Keeping a single `CompositeDisposable` or a plain `Array<() ⇒ void>` is a good
   277→pattern, as shown earlier.
   278→
   279→```ts
   280→import { CompositeDisposable } from '@paletteflow/studio/utils';
   281→
   282→const subs = new CompositeDisposable();
   283→
   284→export const onActivate = (_ctx: ActivationContext) => {
   285→  const disposeKeybind = globalKeymap.bind('ctrl+shift+c', () => /* … */);
   286→  subs.add(disposeKeybind);
   287→
   288→  return subs; // CompositeDisposable implements dispose()
   289→};
   290→```
   291→
   292→<br>
   293→
   294→## 5. Threading Model & Re-entrancy
   295→
   296→* All hooks run **inside the renderer process** (i.e. a BrowserWindow preload),
   297→  **not** the Node-only main process.  
   298→* Hooks must be designed to be *idempotent*—the host might invoke them again
   299→  after a hot-reload without restarting the entire app.
   300→* Long-running hooks should be async / `Promise`-based to avoid blocking the
   301→  UI thread.
   302→
   303→<br>
   304→
   305→## 6. Common Pitfalls
   306→
   307→1. Forgetting to clean up DOM or canvas event listeners → memory leaks  
   308→2. Performing network requests in `onNodeRender` → jank every frame  
   309→3. Throwing inside `onSettingsChange` with no `onUnhandledError` guard → plugin
   310→   gets auto-disabled by the sandbox  
   311→
   312→Use the provided `logger` to trace runtime behaviour rather than relying on
   313→`console.log`, which may be silenced in production builds.
   314→
   315→<br>
   316→
   317→## 7. Versioning Strategy
   318→
   319→The SDK follows **semver**:
   320→
   321→* **Patch** releases only add backward-compatible hooks
   322→* **Minor** releases may deprecate existing hooks but never remove them
   323→* **Major** releases can delete old hooks — update your `peerDependencies`!
   324→
   325→To future-proof your plugin, always specify a caret range in `package.json`:
   326→
   327→```jsonc
   328→{
   329→  "peerDependencies": {
   330→    "@paletteflow/studio": "^1.8.0"
   331→  }
   332→}
   333→```
   334→
   335→<br>
   336→
   337→---
   338→
   339→© 2024 PaletteFlow — Empowering creatives to think in shapes, not files.
   340→```

